      "content": "\"nostalgic purposes\" is a bit of an understatement, isn't it? we're talking about a luxury hotel. our whole brand is built on knowing exactly how a guest likes their coffee or which side of the bed they prefer before they even ask. \n\nif we purge all that \"historical context\" as the policy suggests, we basically become a generic hotel. it's not just about being nice; it's about the actual functionality of the personalized service you're supposed to provide. \n\ndo you think there's a way to classify those long-term preference files as \"essential\" instead of \"non-essential\" so we don't lose them? i'm trying to see if there's a technical or operational argument i can make to the board to stop this purge.",
